{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01PJXtyqwifJdagpKfYJY4v9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the current state:\n1. CockroachDB is running in insecure mode (--insecure flag)\n2. No TLS secrets exist yet\n3. An openssl-toolbox pod is available for cert generation\n\nI need to:\n1. Generate CA certificate using openssl-toolbox\n2. Generate node certificates for each CockroachDB pod\n3. Generate client certificates (for root user)\n4. Create Kubernetes secrets with these certificates\n5. Update the StatefulSet to mount the certs and remove --insecure flag, add --certs-dir\n\nThe CockroachDB certificate structure requires:\n- CA cert: `ca.crt`\n- Node cert: `node.crt` and `node.key` (with SANs for all pod and service names)\n- Client cert: `client.root.crt` and `client.root.key`\n\nAll certs go into `/cockroach/cockroach-certs`. My plan is to generate the CA key and cert first, then create the node certificate with appropriate SANs, followed by the client certificate, and finally bundle everything into a Kubernetes secret.\n\nNow I need to update the StatefulSet to remove the insecure flag, add the certs directory path, mount the secret volume, and switch the health probes to HTTPS. For the SANs, I need to include localhost, the loopback IP, and all the pod DNS names like `crdb-cluster-0.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local` plus the service names. The key files need restrictive permissions (0600), though the CA key itself won't live on the nodes.\n\nCockroachDB expects a specific cert structure in the mounted directory with ca.crt, node.crt, node.key, client.root.crt, and client.root.key. Since all three pods will share the same node certificate for simplicity, I need to generate it with SANs covering all their FQDNs. I'll use the openssl-toolbox pod to generate these certificates.\n\nGenerating the CA and node certificates... Finishing the certificate generation by adding the client root key and certificate files to the Kubernetes secret, then completing the secret creation command with the remaining certificate files.\n\nNow I'm realizing there's a permissions issue with CockroachDB—the key files need to be readable only by the owner (0600 permissions), but Kubernetes secrets mount files with 0644 by default. I can solve this either by setting `defaultMode: 0600` on the volume mount or using an init container to fix the permissions after mounting, though I need to verify exactly what permission level CockroachDB requires for the key files. == 0 check ensures the key files aren't world-readable, which satisfies CockroachDB's security requirements. I'll proceed with setting `defaultMode: 0400` on the secret volume.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the migration path from insecure to secure mode. When updating the StatefulSet to enable TLS, the rolling restart should work since CockroachDB can handle the transition, though I need to verify whether v24.1 supports mixed-mode communication during the upgrade or if all nodes need to switch simultaneously. I'm leaning toward the simpler rolling restart approach since the data persists in the PVCs, but I'm uncertain whether CockroachDB can handle a mixed secure/insecure state during the transition. The safest path is to scale down to zero first, update the StatefulSet with the new secure configuration, then scale back up—this ensures a clean transition without mixing modes. I'll scale to 0 then back to 3 to force all pods to restart simultaneously with the new configuration. The updated StatefulSet needs to remove the insecure flag, add the certs directory volume and mount, and crucially update the health probes from HTTP to HTTPS since TLS will be enabled on the admin port. Now I'm generating the certificates using openssl...\n\nGenerating TLS certificates... I realize the process substitution won't work in the exec context, so I'm switching to writing the SAN configuration to a temp file first, then referencing it in the certificate generation commands.\n\nGenerating the CA key and certificate with a 10-year validity period, then creating the node key and signing request before issuing the node certificate with the same extended validity...\n\nWriting certificate generation...\n\nNow I need to extract those cert files from the pod and create a Kubernetes secret. I can use `kubectl exec` to read each certificate file's contents and then create the secret with those values. Executing into the toolbox pod to generate the certificates, then using `kubectl cp` to pull them down to a local temp directory, and finally creating the secret from those files with `kubectl create secret` pointing to each certificate file.\n\nFor updating the StatefulSet, I need to switch from `--insecure` mode to `--certs-dir=/cockroach/cockroach-certs`, mount the secret as a volume at that path, update the health check probes to use HTTPS instead, and set the proper file permissions on the secret volume.\n\nWriting the StatefulSet patch... I think the cleaner approach is to fetch the current StatefulSet as JSON, modify it programmatically, and then apply it back. I need to update the command to enable TLS by removing the `--insecure` flag and adding the certificate paths instead.\n\nUpdating the command... Completing the join clause with all three cluster nodes, then configuring the liveness and readiness probes to use HTTPS, and setting up volume mounts for the data directory and certificate secrets. Now I'm reconsidering the strategic merge patch approach for kubectl...\n\nActually, I think the safest path is to generate a complete new StatefulSet manifest and apply it directly rather than trying to patch. My plan is to create the certificates using the openssl toolbox, copy them locally, create the secret, write out the full YAML, scale down the existing StatefulSet, and then apply the new one.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"u